post_text:
Chris Gibowicz is stepping down as the director of curriculum and instruction for ACS. She is looking forward to stepping into her new roll as an instructional coach at AMS.

"I have truly enjoyed my time as the director of curriculum and instruction these last three years,” she said. “But I have deeply missed being a part of a school setting where I am able to help the staff members and take an active role in the students’ education. I feel stepping into this position is the best decision for me right now, and I am thrilled to be able to continue to serve as a member of the Alliance Aviator team."

ACS would like to thank Ms. Gibowicz for all she has done during her time as the director of curriculum and instruction!

Click below for more information. #RepthatA

For parents and students who selected the Alliance Digital Academy for the first semester, Monday, Aug. 17 at 5 p.m., an informational presentation will be released to introduce the parents and students to the Alliance Digital Academy.

We can't wait to welcome our students back to in-person and digital learning!

post_text:
Aviators,

We are looking forward to returning for the 2020-2021 School Year in the fall! This school year will look a little different due to the unprecedented time we are living in. Within the coming weeks, we will be releasing our reopening plan for the start of the school year. This plan will include the options of face-to-face schooling or connected remote learning for each grade depending on which option is selected by individual families.

Ensuring the health and wellbeing of our students, staff and families is our top priority at this time. Please be on the lookout for our full plan to be released within the coming weeks.

#RepthatA

post_text:
ACS is hosting Camp Invention - Camp Connect this summer. Students are able to participate in camp from their homes. All materials will be sent directly to campers. Scholarships are being offered which will allow camp to cost $15 per camper due to funding from our partners of George H. Deuble Foundation and the Greater Alliance Foundation.

This year the modules will include learning about simple machines and creating a sports complex, learning about flight and creating hand copters and paper airplanes, learning about the design process and creating a new invention, and learning about the environment and completing challenges.

If students are interested, camp registration can be completed here:
https://invent-web.ungerboeck.com/programsearch/moreinfo.aspx?event=30962

#RepthatA

post_text:
The AHS Academic Challenge team recently competed in a nation-wide, online tournament. The team placed 3rd in Ohio and in the top 50% in the country!

The Academic Challenge team is also in the middle of a tournament against AHS Academic Challenge alumni. The current students won part one of the tournament while the alumni are ahead after outscoring the current students in part two. The tournament will conclude this Friday as the teams compete against each other in a live lightning round via Zoom which will be moderated by former advisor, Mr. James Ballor.

#RepthatA

post_text: ACS would like to thank Mr. Ben Curtis, former PGA golfer, and his foundation, https://www.bencurtisfoundation.org/birdie-bags/, that helps feed local youth. He recently donated over 750 "birdie bags" to ACS for distribution to our students and families. The bags were full of nine meals, six snacks and one travel size toiletry kit (shampoo, conditioner, body wash and toothpaste). Thank you, Mr. Curtis, for helping to support our students! #RepthatA

post_text: Aviators, take a look! #RepthatA
shared_text:
Scott and Jen's Burger Hut
March 31 at 5:59 PM ·

We would like to let everyone know that we had a local business man by the name of Roger Steed with Steed Family Properties donate 1,000 Cheeseburger and Small Fry meals to the community !! We are truly blessed and greatful that he has chosen us to do this for him !
This will start tomorrow Wednesday the 1st at 1pm and we will be handing out Free Cheeseburger and Small Fries until they are gone ! No matter if it takes a few days !
We just ask that everyone be safe first and abide by the laws of this shutdown , caused by the Coronavirus .. No more than 10 people in lobby at once and please keep the 6ft rule in mind also . Everyone just have patience and we will get this done !
Thank you Roger for choosing the Burger Hut to show your gratitude... We really appreciate it and will do our best for you ! You are a great Man !!!! Thank you ...
Have a great day and be Safe !!!!

post_text:
Preschool & Kindergarten Registration is from Mar. 23-27! Here is some FAQs about Kindergarten and Preschool you should know!

Q: When are the times for AM and PM Preschool?
A: The times are as follows - AM is 9:05-11:50 a.m. PM is 1-3:45 p.m.

Q: What time is Kindergarten?
A: Kindergarten is from 9:05 a.m. - 3:45 p.m.

Q: Where do I turn in my packet?
A: Your packet is to be turned into the Registration Office at AHS, Door #2.

Q: When are the registration packets due?
A: There is no official due date. The Registrar will be accepting packets all summer. If you want a specific teacher or time, turning them in sooner would be helpful in getting your child placed in the requested room/time and assuring you a spot. Spots fill up quickly!

More information about Preschool & Kindergarten Registration can be found here: http://www.alliancecityschools.org/article/202475?org=alliance-city-school-district

#RepthatA

post_text: The kindergarten students at AELS are finishing up their Valentine mail projects as the end of February draws near! This project was a huge success! Between the 10 classes, they received 870 pieces of mail from every state in America. They even received mail from Puerto Rico, Ukraine, France, England, Hong Kong, Ireland, Italy, Germany, Canada and Spain! A United States Navy ship out at sea heard about the project and had every officer send a Valentine card. It is incredible how much the children learned about different people and places from the letters. We appreciate anyone who spread the word and sent letters! Thank you! #RepthatA

post_text: AELS kindergarteners completed a mini-unit focusing on kindness and acts of kindness. Each classroom participated in various activities centered around showing kindness to all. Some classrooms created Valentine’s Day cards for patients in nursing homes, while others practiced friendship by communicating with pen pals in Germany. They created acrostic poems using the word ‘kindness’ to brainstorm words or ideas associated with being kind and being a good friend. Students listened to stories and charted actions that are kind versus actions that could be considered unkind. To culminate the unit, all 200 students came together to form a picture spelling out the word ‘kind’ with their bodies. The picture will be displayed at AELS as a reminder of how we can practice kindness every day! #RepthatA

A small act of kindness has the power to change a person's entire day. Yesterday, the AMS Academic Challenge team did just that by choosing to be kind and holding up signs saying "We love you!" The kind gesture was caught by Ms. Ford, who was touched by the thoughtful students.

At ACS, we value caring citizens and that is what those students chose to be yesterday. We are very proud of these students and hope their act of kindness will inspire others to do the same.

Thank you, Ms. Ford, for sharing your story with us! We are glad our students were able to make your day a little brighter. #RepthatA

post_text: Erica Thompson and Deborah Kelley's class has been having so much fun with music! The children have been learning about different types of music like orchestras and bands, classical music versus band music. They have been learning the names of different instruments and hearing their sounds and even had some guests come in to play various instruments including a flute, drums, trumpet, clarinet and bassoon! The children have also had fun being in their own band and playing instruments each day of the week! Music is so much fun! #RepthatA

The kindergarten students are receiving Valentine's Day cards! Each class reads their cards and puts a sticker on the map to see where their new friends live in the USA. They are making a lot of new friends all across the United States!

There is still plenty of time to send cards to the students and to help them achieve their goal of receiving at least one card from every state!

Help the kindergarteners out with this fun project by sending a Valentine's Day card to:

Alliance Early Learning School
285 W. Oxford
Alliance, OH 44601.

The cards can be addressed to any of the following classes:
Mrs. Harper/Mrs. Gaines
Mrs. Gasparik
Mrs. Johnson
Mrs. Bowser
Mrs. Reich
Mrs. Morgan
Mrs. Gibbons
Ms. Hennon
Mrs. Winner
Ms. Elliott
Ms. Zemrock/Mrs. Hackney

Please be sure to include your address so the students know where to mark the map!

One murder, twenty suspects. Who killed the Mysterious Host? Could it be the Respected General? What about the Wealthy Dowager? Or maybe it was Santa Claus. The mystery unfolds as the Inexplicably Omniscient Inspector takes on the most thrilling and baffling murder case in the history of thrilling and baffling murder cases.

The show is free to attend and promises plenty of laughs and mind-boggling entertainment! We hope to see you there!

#RepthatA

post_text:
Students in Crystal Gibbons’ class recently finished a learning unit on Winter Wonderland, where they learned about all things winter! They read the book "The Snowy Day" and discussed all the things that Peter did in the snow.

Afterwards, the kids made a snow picture out of fake snow (shaving cream and glue). They were able to create all of the activities that Peter did: draw in the snow, make tracks in the snow, etc. They added a paper Peter cut-out to finish their pictures. The next day, the students did a retelling of the story and completed comprehension activities about the book.

Each student was given their very own copy of the book to take home from our monthly book sponsors! #RepthatA

post_text: The students in Lori Gasparik's class at AELS learned about snow and snowflakes during the Winter Wonderland Unit. They examined a variety of snowflakes and their unique shapes. After going outside and observing the falling snow, the students came back in and created their own snowflakes. They learned that no two snowflakes are identical... just like children! #RepthatA
